And while I'm taking midterm examinations, the proctor comes in and says, are you Clarence Jones? And I said, yes, I am. He said, well, there is an emergency call for you. You need to go to the dean's office.

190
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:20,000
Now, ironically, I was taking this midterm examination on my birthday, January 8th, 1952. I go to the dean's office and I said, Mr. Jones, we got a call from the hospital in Camden, New Jersey.

191
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:37,000
Cooper's hospital, I mean, Cooper's something hospital, and I said, yes, apparently, we Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know the details, which are mothers in the hospital. You need to call this number immediately.

192
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:56,000
So, you know, I'm trying to decide. So I call, I said, essentially, my father was so broken up, he was a really difficult, he was a communicator, a doctor got on the phone and said,

193
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:21,000
we, your mother, we just operate on your mother. And we had to ask your father's consent. They had to take her a bowel track out, do a coloscopy in a bag, because she has cancer in her rectum.

194
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:45,000
A abdominal rectal cancer, and she probably has about three or four months to live. I mean, I'm, so I, I go back and I say to the proctor, it was an S, I said,

195
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:56,000
I, I want to try to see if I can send 15 minutes to try to finish where I am in the exam. So I finished and it in my paper.

196
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:14,000
And I went to, got on the bus, or go to the hospital. And it was, it was just, all this was a shock to me. My father was just in, in, in, in, in, consultable grief.

197
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:38,000
So, we bring my mother home, in the hospital. When I talk to the doctor, and I'm talking to my mother. And she is very upset that I am there.

198
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:54,000
That she, she was started to cry, why are you here? You should be in school. I said, well, my mother, her and so forth. She said, no, no, no, no, mom is going to be alright. You've got to go back to school. So I mean, I talked to the doctor.

199
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:07,000
And, and he says, well, Mr. Jones, this is what it is. You know, I went in to see the dean of college.

200
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:14,000
And my attitude was, you know, I can always get an education.

201
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:28,000
This is, this is, this is my mother, you know. So I wanted to, I wanted to take a leave of absence. I wanted to drop out, take a leave of absence. He says, no, I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't think you need to do that clearance.

202
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:37,000
Why Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't we work out something where you just, you just stay. And we'll work out something with your classes, you know, you try to keep up.

203
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:59,000
And I had some friends and so, so what I did was that I, I stayed in school. But I set up, I put a, I put a desk at the foot of my mother's bed in her bedroom. And I swear I did all my homework.

204
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:17,000
And I had to leave periodically to go back to New York. I also had to leave to keep some credibility with her because she refused to believe that in fact I had permission to study. She just refused to believe that she would cry.

205
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:22,000
You know, Mama, what you're going to have an education is an education. Okay.

206
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:35,000
May 4th, 1952 she dies. She's buried on May 8th.

207
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:55,000
When they, she was 160 pounds about, tall, five foot, 10, 155, 60 pounds.

208
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:08,000
She died. She was about 99 pounds, less than 99 pounds. They took her body out from the mattress and took her to the undertaker place.

209
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:27,000
And when they removed her body and they were removing the bed things, you know, I saw that there was a letter under the mattress that she had written to me.

210
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:43,000
All during the time she was six, she was carrying on this charade. And Mama's going to get better. Mama's going to get better. You know, she's going to be, not going to be as different.

211
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:51,000
I'm going to have to get adjusted to doing things. But Mama's going to get better. We're going to get better. She was losing more weight anyway.

212
00:39:51,000 --> 00:40:06,000
So she leaves this letter to me. And the essence of the letter is that she's apologizing to me. She's asking, my forgiveness for leaving me.

213
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:27,000
She's asking, my forgiveness. And she's talking about how proud I have made her feel that no mother, she says, could ask for a son that could bring her great joy.

214
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:47,000
And then my favorite, she was a cook, one of the best cooks in the world. And she, I was a dessert, you know, how I'm so to speak. And so she knew that the things that she homemade for me were crullers and a dessert called floating island.

215
00:40:48,000 --> 00:41:10,000
And she says, she says, I'm Mama's sorry she can't be here to make crullers and floating island. But I wrote the recipe down for you. And I'm sorry to leave you, but you know, I know that someday you're going to be a great man.

216
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:23,000
I know you're going to be a great man and always try to be good and always try to make me proud because I know I am so proud of you. And someday you're going to be a great man.

217
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:30,000
I'm sorry I have to leave you. Please forgive me.

218
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:42,000
Okay. Well, let me tell you something. I was an only child, I know your brother's sister.

219
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:59,000
I spent a limited amount of time with my parents. But as I begin going forward in my life and I measured things in terms of how difficult they were or how painful they were.

220
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:12,000
It became very clear that my internal gyroscope was founded on the following.

221
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:27,000
I had been to the apex and the mountaintop of pain. I couldn't conceive of anything happening in my life thereafter.

222
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:40,000
I couldn't conceive of anything thereafter, having a more profound effect of loss in anguish and the loss of my mother.

223
00:42:40,000 --> 00:43:03,000
So, when I would study and read the political history of China, and I would see that Chou and Lai, when a great Chinese political leader says the strongest steel, is tempered by the hottest fire.

224
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:17,000
I knew what he was saying. It also conditioned me to have the dialectic of compassion and strength.

225
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:34,000
Okay. So, that for example, the Korean War broke out in June 25th, 1950. I was a student.

226
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:46,000
As a student, I was entitled to a student deferment.

227
00:43:46,000 --> 00:44:09,000
Because in the aftermath of my mother's death, in 52, I was scheduled to graduate in 53, because in order to sustain, maintain your exemption, your student deferment, either had to graduate or you had to be full-time in school.

228
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:16,000
And if you were a nearing graduation, you had to have made an application to a graduate school.

229
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:29,000
Okay. And if you didn't have either of those things, you were not entitled to exempt me, exempt from the job.

230
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:50,000
So, my job board snatched me, because I was in the space. I was drafted in August 12th, 1953.

231
00:44:51,000 --> 00:45:08,000
I was angry. I had also become politicized in college.

232
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:20,000
I had also met in New York to my uncle, an extraordinary man, who I didn't even know who he was.

233
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:27,000
I heard you, I saw him and went to see him in a Broadway play, but then I found that he was an actor with Paul Robson.

234
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:36,000
I went to see him in Othello or on Whitman Avenue or something. I went to see him in something with Uta Hagen on Broadway.

235
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:47,000
And my uncle had become friends with him. And when I was in Columbia, I had two instances with Paul Robson.

236
00:45:47,000 --> 00:46:02,000
I had been active politically in college. This is before my mother died in 1952, but that whole area between 1949 and 1952 had been active and so forth.

237
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:13,000
And I loved football in addition to all the other things. But if you loved football, you either played football in Baker's Field as a part of the Columbia team,

238
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:24,000
or if you went to a football game, and I was not varsity, but I was in line with the varsity team.

239
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:32,000
So I would go to every football team, every Saturday, I'd be up at Baker's Field at Columbia, New York.

240
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:41,000
And my classmates who were more politically inclined would say, well, you know, when we have to hand out leaflets, you never hand out any leaflets, you're never there.

241
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:54,000
You're never there, you know, you need a committee and I commit it. So I told Paul Robson this story once I was so I'm socially with my uncle Leda, party, and I told him that story.

242
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:12,000
He was tall and big, and he says, you know, you go back and you tell your white, liberal progressive friends, I have lots of white progressive friends,

243
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:33,000
but you go back and tell your white progressive friends who are students, that one touchdown on a Saturday afternoon by you, a Negro in Baker's Field with that stadium filled with almost 50,000 people.

244
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:48,000
One touchdown have greater impact on getting white people to understand the equality of Negroes than anything they could ever write in those leaflets.

245
00:47:48,000 --> 00:48:03,000
And I was like, this is for us, never would we get that. The other instance that influenced on me is that he at this time was being summoned before the House of American Activities Committee.

246
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:09,000
And I watched him on television.

247
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:26,000
So let me just, let me just, you go back and look at the archives, I would suggest you go back and look at Paul Robson appearing before the House Internal Security Committee, the House on American Communities Committee, but it was chaired by James Eastland from Mississippi.

248
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:40,000
And when Paul Robson was being asked, the sit is sworn in as a witness by the chairman, he stands up for six foot, four or six foot, he says, you, he points his finger at him.

249
00:48:40,000 --> 00:49:01,000
You Mr. Wieslin, you are unconstitutionally seated in that chair. You Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't have the authority, the constitutional hourly authority to ask me any questions whatsoever because you were illegally sitting in this Congress.

250
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:18,000
You were illegally because of the mass exclusion of my people invoting. You have no authority whatsoever to ask me any questions. I said, wow, that was a bad dude.

251
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:39,000
Okay, I mean it influenced me, okay. So my mother dies, influenced Paul Robson, my anger, not getting exempted. So when I report the night before the induction, by the way, I had some left wing.

252
00:49:39,000 --> 00:50:02,000
I'm not going to say they were communist because I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know that they were communist. It was the young, young friends of mine, but they were members of the Labor Youth League, which was supposed to have been a communist-affiliated organization, but they were left, but they were very, they were just great friends of mine.

253
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:05,000
I had a...

254
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:12,000
What was the effect of inter-refuge for a second when you were talking about your friends that were illegal being it? Is this the same group or is this the same kind of politics there?

255
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:27,000
No, no, no, these were different. There were friends, they were an extended group. They weren't necessarily, the Paul Robson comments were meant to my friends who, yes, I said, no matter if they were the same. They were substantially the same.

256
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:35,000
But I had become friends with... And one woman by the name of Judith Treesman, Judy, I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know whether you're alive, whether you have a...

257
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:44,000
Here, this is a seedest, but I had such admiration for her and her family treated me like I was just part of their family, great warmth.

258
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:54,000
And I remember Judy Treesman. I mean, that was where she was at the young woman at that time. I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know where it is today, but at that time she says, you know,

259
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:03,000
you know, you know, you Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want to go. If you Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want to report, you know, maybe you just think about it.

260
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:12,000
If you want to go to Canada or if you Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want to go to Canada, I think you should go to Eastern Europe, Czechoslovakia and so forth like that.

261
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:19,000
No, no, no, no, and then she says, well, you know, she said, Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't get the wrong idea. You know, I parents like you and I like you.

262
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:26,000
And I mean, I really care about you. So all I'm simply saying, if you wanted to go and I said, I'd go with you, if I would make it easy for you.

263
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:31,000
You know, and I find something to do. And I said, what are you talking about? She says, yeah, I would do that.

264
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:39,000
You know, because I know you're hurting. I know you Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want to go. And I said, no, Judy, I can't do that. But I seriously thought about it.

265
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:48,000
I seriously thought about it. But as a result of the anger of being inductive and I didn't think I should have been inducted,

266
00:51:48,000 --> 00:52:08,000
in my draft board in Mt. Holly, New Jersey, I signed from Richard Vilariani, who was a news, who went to Burlington, high school in Burlington, New Jersey.

267
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:29,000
There were very few college students. And I still did this day believe that this this this prejudice in Manholy draft board saying, well, we'll send this Negro, you know, draft them, who's they think he is.

268
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:38,000
I mean, I think if I think I had been white, I wouldn't think I'd have been drafted. I think I just said, oh, he's a role to Columbia College.

269
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:46,000
And yes, he had a problem with this. I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't think that a draft of me has mother died. No, they didn't. They didn't care. So I was bitter.

270
00:52:46,000 --> 00:53:02,000
So the night before I was to report for induction, I sat down and wrote a handwritten note as to why I was reporting for induction, but why I was not going to serve in the Army.

271
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:19,000
And I in the course of the note, I said, in effect, I said, I'm willing to go and serve and and and give my life for my country as a member of the United States Army.

272
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:33,000
When my country cheese me as a first class citizen, I'm not willing to put my life on the line in a war that I have lots of questions about the Korean War, lots of questions, but I'm not willing to do that.

273
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:52,000
And so therefore I'm reporting for induction and I cited the first. I wasn't a lawyer. I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know anything. I mean, I was educated or being excited the first, the fifth, the 14th and 15th of members of the Constitution.

274
00:53:53,000 --> 00:54:18,000
As a reason I was not. So I'm in Whitehall Street, New York. I report for duty August 13th early in the morning. Now, have you seen some of these military pictures? When you report to duty, the first thing the non-commissioned officer says, and it was a Negro, non-commissioned officer, he says, all right, Cece, okay.

275
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:32,000
You raise your hand, you know, you're being inducted to the Army. Well, I didn't raise my hand, you know, because I figured if I didn't, if I didn't consent to this, they couldn't, so I didn't raise my hand.

276
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:45,000
So I'm listening to all this ramp about, you know, your ass is grass now, you know, you're in the Army, you belong to us.

277
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And then Sergeant, he says, well, what's with you? What's with you soldier? And I said, there's nothing, I just, I said, I'm here when reporting.

278
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:13,000
What are you some kind of cook or conscientious objective? And I said, no. And then I gave him a statement to read. And he read it, he said, what are you some kind of commie? I said, no. He said, well, get out of line.

279
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:23,000
So he puts me out of line. And then they, they, a captain, a white captain officer comes over and so what's the problem?

280
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:39,000
Private Jones, what's the problem with Mr. Jones, he said. I said, well, I realize I'm here because I want to show up. But I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't, these are my reasons why I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want to serve sir.

281
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:50,000
I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't think I think I'm being unfairly treated and I want to serve you, read it. And that's when he says, oh, he said, we better come over here.

282
00:55:50,000 --> 00:56:05,000
And they had some kind of conference for about two or three, but two hours. Whatever they decided, oh, yeah, whatever they decided you go, they were going to put me on the bus to Fort Dix.

283
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:17,000
So I go to Fort Dix. And somebody at Fort Dix had been alerted that I was on the bus and coming. Now, in the Fort Dix, that's when they, that's when it gets serious.

284
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:33,000
Because that's when they want you to sign up for your, your insurance, you sign, you're going to get paid, the issue your clothes, you know, you, you, and so they kept saying, you know, you know, sign this, you know, you're not going to get any money.

285
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:48,000
I said, I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't care. I'm not signing anything. What? Well, if you can't sign, you're not going to have any insurance. You're not going to, you're not going to get any paycheck. You're not going to get anything. I said, I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't care. I'm not signing anything.

286
00:56:48,000 --> 00:57:07,000
So they issue me, they issue me standard things, they put me and they process me to go for basic training. But no, stop there. Before they process me, I take, I take examinations, okay, placement examination.

287
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:21,000
Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't do so. So about three or four days after I take the placement examination, I find that they're putting me in a group that scheduled to go to some place in Maryland.

288
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:34,000
Because we're going to be part of some special forces team, so special forces intelligence team. So I said, I think there must be some mistake.

289
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:56,000
So I remember going to one of these two orientation things. I'm listening. And I'm talking about how they're going to, we're going to be trained as going to the special unit. Some of us may go to California to the Army language school to learn Russian or Polish, principally that.

290
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:07,000
I'm thinking to myself and then I put it all together. Because I talked to some of the other soldiers who were all gone ho about this. They're going to send you to Fort Jackson to Parachupir School and so forth.

291
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:24,000
The bottom line is that they were being trained to be special ops who would jump at night behind me in lines in a Soviet Union and pull on the Czechoslovakia. So I said, so I'm laughing while I find out I said, now, this is after they go to the Army language school.

292
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:39,000
So I said, now, now let's assume that I go through all this and I'm fluent in Russian. How am I going to explain this black face of mine as I show up in the Russian countryside, the Polish countryside? I said, this is crazy. It's crazy.

293
00:58:39,000 --> 00:59:06,000
I mean, that's on saying the military was at the point. But anyway, so I, I, I mean, the whole of it and I was bitter, angry over the death of my mother and really, and really, I really began to, I was influenced by Paul Rupsen and I figured I, you know, and, and I also trying to find a way of getting out. I'm not doing it.

294
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:24,000
I just wanted to ask, this is a good time, I think, to ask, what other influences beyond Rupsen? I mean, with the people that you were reading, had, had looking back, you know, this is a very device. What do you think inspired us?

295
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:47,000
I think my friends, I had become, I had become, I become friends with a lot of New York student leftists who had become, in one case, a couple of cases had become very dear friends of mine.

296
00:59:48,000 --> 01:00:06,000
In one case, I can think of as a poet by the name of Robert Barron Numeroff. Robert Nemiroff was getting a master's degree in English from NYU. We became, he even got a Columbia, he went to NYU.

