She heard me play warm up. The best thing I can tell you was that it blew her away because I sat down when she was just watching this thing. I said, why Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't I play for you? The Mozart clarinet concerto in A for you to listen to you. You just sit over there and I'll play. She was stunned.

435
01:32:33,000 --> 01:33:02,000
The next week, this is in Wilton, Connecticut. The next week, she arranges for there to be a chamber music group in which her son-in-law is going to be the clarinetist in which we played Brahms, Mozart, but things for clarinet and strings and cello and flute are primarily written by Brahms and Mozart Beethoven writing some things.

436
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:32,000
And then, of course, I would perform solo pieces like Flight of the Bumblebee. That single act made my mother alone go out of her way to tell other people about how she wanted them to meet me and how he's been able to play the piano.

437
01:33:33,000 --> 01:34:01,000
It was busy, but we want him to come up here every weekend because you have to see him and so forth as a person. And I write one of my books. I write one of my books when she heard me play the Mozart clarinet concerto. It was a whole. She heard me play this before we had any children because no one had children.

438
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:13,000
Now, had you and Anne talked about what life might be like for you as an interracial couple at that time, or did you have other examples of couples that you knew?

439
01:34:13,000 --> 01:34:27,000
Well, Charlie White was a black artist married to a white woman, a fan baron.

440
01:34:27,000 --> 01:34:44,000
And I say this, not in criticism. And went to the, and went to the The Brearley School, private girl school. She went to Sarah Lawrence and she was in high school. She was raised by a governess.

441
01:34:44,000 --> 01:35:05,000
In addition to having a home in Wilton, her parents had a townhouse on Grammacy Park. And at that time, everybody who owned a townhouse had a key to the park.

442
01:35:05,000 --> 01:35:29,000
So I remember we lived in the head of the townhouse with 17 Grammacy Park. And Anne had a tremendous deep idealism, but also had a certain kind of

443
01:35:29,000 --> 01:35:49,000
sort of nutritionist, certain kind of attitude that she was certain she was right. The classic example, this is after we're living in Boston.

444
01:35:49,000 --> 01:36:13,000
My oldest daughter, the baby, was shopping at a food place and a check out. And Anne had to go back. So Tina Christine was in this little bassinet and we left her right up on the counter, you know, on the other checkout counter.

445
01:36:13,000 --> 01:36:37,000
And I was standing there by, and the checkout counter, I must have returned and somebody said, well, whose little baby is this? You know, not in a negative way. But my wife saw this. And like a lioness, you know, this is what I'm going to say.

446
01:36:37,000 --> 01:36:51,000
And her way of dealing with this. So she's, she's white, fair skin, blonde hair, gray blue eyes, attractive.

447
01:36:51,000 --> 01:37:11,000
Five foot, ten and a half was the way she looked at that white woman behind the counter. This was like, it was like, it was like, it was like, that's what she could do.

448
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:26,000
It was like she looked at this other white person like she was a piece of dirt and how dare she question, how dare she even think about. I mean, that's the other side of Anne.

449
01:37:26,000 --> 01:37:40,000
She had this, that's a kind of instinct she could get. She could become very, for sure. So, so my, my, my answer to your question is that she loved me.

450
01:37:40,000 --> 01:38:07,000
And the question that I think that she felt that she didn't have to ask anybody's approval. She felt she had the resources in the stature. She felt she was raised in an environment where she was part of the upper class.

451
01:38:07,000 --> 01:38:22,000
So she tended to look down on everybody else. Classic example. And I say this, just as an, classic example. Her best friend was a woman by the name of Damon Estate Estate.

452
01:38:22,000 --> 01:38:43,000
Damon Estate Estate was the daughter of the Doe Pineapple people. They were very, very close friends. Back when I got out of, I was ready to graduate from law school. Damon Estate Estate tried to convince. And we should just move to Hawaii. And I said, you know, I said that. I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know what I wanted to do. I moved to Hawaii.

453
01:38:43,000 --> 01:38:55,000
I was, she says, look, Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't worry about it. We, my family will just, we'll, we'll, we'll, clients and you will build you a house. So forth. You know, we'll just so forth.

454
01:38:55,000 --> 01:39:10,000
And I didn't even appreciate who Damon Estate Estate was until I began to, until Anne began to tell me. And then I began to understand that aside from some king's trust,

455
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:22,000
aside from the trust in Hawaii that the Damon Estate's are the second largest landowners in Hawaii. And that was Anne's friends.

456
01:39:22,000 --> 01:39:42,000
But those are the, now the other thing was that Anne had lots of left wing friends too. And I think she was.

457
01:39:42,000 --> 01:39:58,000
Well, objectively, I would have to say we were all living in a state of rebellion. But she, more than I, I think, and I loved her. I think she was rebelling against the fact that she did not like her stepfather.

458
01:39:58,000 --> 01:40:07,000
Or really put it very bluntly. She liked her stepfather, but she couldn't reconcile who he was and what he did.

459
01:40:07,000 --> 01:40:20,000
And, and, and one of the arguments we used to have, she thought that I was too nice to him. Or she would say he's only being nice to you because he wants you to overlook. And I said, Anne, hold on.

460
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:35,000
I said, you're a stepfather. I said, all I know. You know, your mother and, and, and Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh, Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh, they have their life. They're treating us. So in other words, I, I wanted to defuse it and so forth.

461
01:40:35,000 --> 01:40:46,000
It became very clear, however, that Um Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh tended to be more friendly to me than he was to end.

462
01:40:46,000 --> 01:41:03,000
Okay. They had a separate kind of antagonism going on there. But anyway, you asked me to see your question. Well, yeah. I mean, we accepted that as part of the reality. Sometimes that reality would be forced on us, for example.

463
01:41:03,000 --> 01:41:20,000
When we went to Boston and we were looking for a place to live and go to law school, one or two or three places once they found out that we were an interracial couple suddenly the part was not available or something and so forth.

464
01:41:20,000 --> 01:41:33,000
So Anne was not dumb smart. She says, well, this is one apartment that I really like. I think we should have. So what I like to do, let me go and see it. Let me go and look at it.

465
01:41:33,000 --> 01:41:42,000
And if I like it, you trust me. I'm going to come back. I'll show you the diagram. You know, and I'll go back.

466
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:49,000
And if I like it, you'll have to trust me. We're going to sign. I'm going to take this apartment. You know, and I'll tell them that.

467
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:55,000
You know, my husband is a student lawyer, but he's and he'll come up and sign the lease later.

468
01:41:55,000 --> 01:42:04,000
Okay. So this is because we've already had to at least two, maybe three instances where we have an apartment fall through.

469
01:42:04,000 --> 01:42:17,000
So finally, I go to this apartment at 857 Beacon Street and as an Irish superintendent and he's a little astounded to see that I am the Mr. Jones.

470
01:42:17,000 --> 01:42:25,000
Okay. That's whom he has rented to his wife. Okay. And he had the stick Irish broke.

471
01:42:25,000 --> 01:42:34,000
And the first thing I said to him, I said, Mr. So-and-so, I said, that broke you have his music to my ears.

472
01:42:34,000 --> 01:42:46,000
I haven't heard that since I was in boarding school with Irish nuns. He looked at me. He says, you were what? I said, yes, I was in boarding school.

473
01:42:46,000 --> 01:43:03,000
And I said, in fact, the one that I had the most love was a Sister Mary Patrician. And she said to me, she made me promise when I grew up, grow up, that I would one day go to the Visitor Island.

474
01:43:03,000 --> 01:43:11,000
And she used to sing to me. She used to sing Danny Boy. And he listened to me. And he said, oh, really?

475
01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:18,000
He says, well, let me show you around the apartment. So I just told him around the apartment and he asked me some questions.

476
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:32,000
And I told him I had been an altar boy, an altar boy at the midnight mass and at Easter services. And I kept saying how much I owed to the Irish nuns.

477
01:43:32,000 --> 01:43:42,000
And that's why I was so, it was music to my ear to hear that. Well, he said, come on downstairs. I want you to introduce you to my wife.

478
01:43:42,000 --> 01:43:50,000
He's the superintendent of the building now. So his wife is in there. So we take him downstairs and he goes to the refrigerator and he opens up some beers.

479
01:43:50,000 --> 01:44:01,000
We sit and talk. So we have a couple of beers and so forth. And as he's drinking, he's becoming more loose and so forth. He says now.

480
01:44:01,000 --> 01:44:08,000
He says, you know, I think they're probably going to have shit of brick.

481
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:19,000
This is what he says. They're going to shit of brick when they find out that you're a Negro. But this is my building. I'm the superintendent of this building.

482
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:26,000
And your wife is signed at least. And I approve of you. And you got a good lease. Welcome to the building.

483
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:37,000
Okay. Okay. That's okay. That's all right. He then that couple became two of our, they were the superintendent.

484
01:44:37,000 --> 01:44:43,000
And the other thing they liked is that all the other people, all the other tenants in the building, you know, they didn't fraternize with them.

485
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:51,000
But because he was so nice, my wife would frequently ask them the superintendent of the building to come and have dinner with us, come and do something.

486
01:44:51,000 --> 01:45:05,000
So this man just fell in love with me. You could any fell in love with Anne. Okay. And and and and we used to talk a lot of baseball.

487
01:45:05,000 --> 01:45:18,000
We were, we used to talk about Fenway Park with just a couple of bucks away from my apartment. And and he was, he developed a certain pride in me.

488
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:37,000
And he was, they used to babysit for us. And he would say, and he would say, you know, he said, you, he said, we were dinner. He says, you know, he said, you know, you know, you're the only, I've never, I've never, I've never sat down and drank with. I never talked to any, I never any talked to any Negro before.

489
01:45:37,000 --> 01:45:45,000
I just never talked to, I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't know why it's a North Turkdom. I Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't have anything against them. I just never talked to them. You know, I mean, this is the way he was.

490
01:45:45,000 --> 01:45:52,000
But that's the reason we got that apartment. And so I got that apartment, we got that apartment because of those Irish nuns.

491
01:45:52,000 --> 01:46:02,000
Because I said, I said, when he's broken his broken, it was very distant. I said, she's, I haven't heard that music to my ears. And I so startled her to hear me say that.

492
01:46:02,000 --> 01:46:08,000
And so I said here again, the Irish nuns were looking out for me. I mean, that's how I got.

493
01:46:08,000 --> 01:46:18,000
By the way, it was a magnificent apartment on the top floor of 857 Beacon Street. You see all of it was a number that was like the top floor apartment.

494
01:46:18,000 --> 01:46:23,000
And that's where I went to law school.

495
01:46:23,000 --> 01:46:35,000
And then, I think this is an interest of time, you know, move forward into your entertainment law career.

496
01:46:35,000 --> 01:46:38,000
And then your introduction to Dr. King.

497
01:46:38,000 --> 01:46:55,000
Well, I did, I did, when I was in law school, as I said, a Fran Barrett and Charlie White.

498
01:46:55,000 --> 01:47:01,000
Fran Barrett was my wife's closest friend aside from Damon Estate Estate, who lived in Hawaii.

499
01:47:01,000 --> 01:47:07,000
They moved from Riverside, they moved from New York City to California.

500
01:47:07,000 --> 01:47:17,000
And when they moved to California, my wife began to long. Okay, she really missed them and said, we gotta go out and visit them.

501
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:26,000
And in my senior year in law school, I took a course in copyright law.

502
01:47:26,000 --> 01:47:42,000
And during that time, copyright law had an essay, a competition called the Nathan Burkan Memorial Copyright Competition,

503
01:47:42,000 --> 01:47:49,000
in which students taking copyright law would write on some esoteric topic.

504
01:47:49,000 --> 01:47:53,000
The country was divided into four quadrants, the Northeast Quadrants, and so forth.

505
01:47:53,000 --> 01:48:01,000
So in the Northeast Quadrant, it was Harvard, Yale, Boston University, Dartmouth, University of Pennsylvania, Syracuse, and so forth.

506
01:48:01,000 --> 01:48:14,000
Because I was a musician, I wrote a paper called the Judicial Criteria, Employed, to determine musical copyright infringement.

507
01:48:14,000 --> 01:48:21,000
I mean, I wrote the paper showing how the courts, I mean, I did it in renaissance.

508
01:48:21,000 --> 01:48:26,000
The paper didn't win for the Northeast Quadrant, but it got honorable mention.

509
01:48:26,000 --> 01:48:37,000
In other words, there was a winning paper in each quadrant, and then one paper was chosen among the four, but in each quadrant, there was always a second one.

510
01:48:37,000 --> 01:48:55,000
So I got the honorable mention. So my, my, my, my, my copy, my professor was blown away. He says, you know, and since I was a little bit older, I'd gone to law school three years later than if I had just gone from college to law school.

511
01:48:55,000 --> 01:49:09,000
And so we became friendly, you know, we became friendly. It wasn't just professor and student was like, Donald Shapiro, you know, he was professor.

512
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:18,000
And he's, one day we're having coffee, maybe drinks in and out. He says, you know, Clarence, he says, you really got a real knack for this.

513
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:31,000
And he says, he says, you know, any entertainment business, he says most Negroes are before the camera or on the footlights or on stages.

514
01:49:31,000 --> 01:49:42,000
And I'm not in any way trying to diminish that talent. He says, but that's not where the real power is. That's not where the decision, the variance in the entertainment business, it's behind.

515
01:49:42,000 --> 01:49:51,000
And I think that's where the people who make the decisions, the people who finance the distribution agreement and so forth. And you got a real knack for this.

516
01:49:51,000 --> 01:50:02,000
And I think you ought to consider going into entertainment law. I have a friend who's a general counsel of Revue Productions, but a name of Leslie Scharlaw.

517
01:50:02,000 --> 01:50:25,000
And I'm going to suggest that you go out there and work. And so you go to California. And that's what I did. I went to California to go to work at, as in the office of Leslie Scharlaw, as in this, you know, just starting out.

518
01:50:25,000 --> 01:50:34,000
I had to take the California bar, which I started to study for, but I had to do, you know.

519
01:50:34,000 --> 01:50:43,000
And in fact, the thing I remember is Sandy Dennis and Bobby Darin, there were two stars.

520
01:50:43,000 --> 01:50:55,000
They used to come sit on my desk in Revue Productions lot. And Bobby Darin had a very kind of openness. He says, now, he says, no, Clarence, where did you come from?

521
01:50:55,000 --> 01:51:03,000
Oh, he says, they Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't even, they Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't even, they Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't even have Negro sleeping at the stages. Where did you come from? You dropped from Mars. How did you get here?

522
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:20,000
So were you going to talk to less, well, less, less, tell me as you go, we're not as you. Leslie Scharlaw, you know. So they were trying to, they were trying to be a friend me. And Sandy would say, you got to watch your back. Sandy Dennis would say, you know, you got to be, you got to be above.

523
01:51:20,000 --> 01:51:28,000
He says, she would say, you see all these cuties around here. Look at that. You got to be above. Watch your back.

524
01:51:29,000 --> 01:51:43,000
I'm there like three, four months, somewhere between one and six months. Leslie Scharlaw dies of a heart attack.

525
01:51:43,000 --> 01:51:48,000
They come all the way out here to go.

526
01:51:48,000 --> 01:52:00,000
So he dies. And he's the power. He's the general counsel. He's the guy. He's Donald Shapiro's friends. So it's like my Godfather's gone.

527
01:52:00,000 --> 01:52:09,000
And people around him and also wonder why is this guy here anyway? You know someone, Leslie Scharlaw is, nobody complained about my work. They complained about my, very clear.

528
01:52:09,000 --> 01:52:29,000
They, very clear. There was very uncomfortable. So I left. And I was thinking about what I was going to do. When I got a call in February, 1960, from Judge Hubert T. Delany,

529
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:38,000
much of what I'm going to tell you has been repeated. You probably seen interviews. So not verbatim, but a substantial, the same subject matter. I tell people how I met Dr. King.

530
01:52:38,000 --> 01:52:50,000
It's in the book. We read the book. You'll see how I tell. He had been indicted by the state of Alabama for tax evasion for perjury with him.

531
01:52:50,000 --> 01:53:05,000
Judge Hubert T. Delany, Negro judge lawyer, was a chief defense counsel along with three other lawyers. Two of the lawyers were from Chicago. Very elite tax attorneys. The other lawyer was a local lawyer, but they were Fred Gray.

532
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:16,000
Civil rights, he was a local person. But they needed a law clerk. A clerk who would go down and coordinate. So Judge Hubert T. Delany says, you know, clearance.

533
01:53:16,000 --> 01:53:29,000
I know you and we're defending this. And I'd love for you to come down and be our law clerk and help us with the defense. And I said, Judge, I'd love to do it, but I'm here in Altadena, California. I can't do it. No way I can do that.

534
01:53:29,000 --> 01:53:41,000
No, no, you know, this is a, this is, if you met him, I said, no, he says, well, you know, this is a, this is a very special time, you know, and I might be the, anyway, he made a great, and it was very difficult.

535
01:53:41,000 --> 01:53:53,000
This is the man that recommended me to Boston University of Alaska. This is the person who was a judge, he was a senior. I mean, he was very, very great partner. For me to say no to him, you know, it was, was not easy.

536
01:53:53,000 --> 01:54:04,000
But I said, no, I couldn't, I said, no, for practical purpose, I couldn't go. And so my wife at that time was pregnant with our second child. I was comfortable going.

537
01:54:04,000 --> 01:54:22,000
And you knew obviously my, no, I never met him before. I vaguely heard of him. You know, I tell everybody I was in law school from 1956 and 1959. I didn't know anything. I mean, I knew about the Montgomery bus boycott, but I was studying. I didn't have time to follow the legal feature. What he's doing?

538
01:54:22,000 --> 01:54:36,000
You know, I mean, I was really not focused on that, you know. So the judge was very disappointed in me. The next thing I know it, that was on a Thursday night on Friday morning. I got another call from the judge and he says, Clarence, I did not know it at the time of our conversation.

539
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:43,000
But Dr. King is on his way to California right now. He has a speaking engagement at the World Affairs Council.

540
01:54:43,000 --> 01:55:04,000
And I told on Saturday evening and I told him, if he does nothing else before he goes through the speaking engagement. And I think he's also going to feature out there. He says, he says, I told him he has to find a way in meeting and talking to you. So I'm thinking to myself, okay, you know what I mean? I'm listening to the judge. And I'm thinking to myself after it.

541
01:55:04,000 --> 01:55:19,000
Why would the judge do that? You know, he's thinking as well. Anyway, maybe just Martin King is going to change my mind. So Friday night doorbell rings. Martin King comes to my home and I'll be in California.

542
01:55:20,000 --> 01:55:40,000
He comes in and he says, you know, he produces himself and comes in with a fellow by the name of Bernard Lee. He comes in to the six around the coffee table on the by the way at that time in February, 1960. Under all classic criteria.

543
01:55:41,000 --> 01:56:05,000
He was a celebrity. He went on the cover of Look, Life, and Time magazines. Plus he had been successful in Montgomery Buzz point got with Rosa Parks. Plus in addition to Supreme Court 1957, it ended down a decision outlawing segregation into state bus transit. He was riding high this feature from Montgomery, okay, in 1960.

544
01:56:06,000 --> 01:56:24,000
So when I told my wife that he was coming, you would have thought in classic current terms that a man of the stature of George Clooney, Denzel Washington, Matt Damon Estate, Matthew McConaughey, Michael Jackson, you know, whoever.

545
01:56:24,000 --> 01:56:41,000
I mean, she was like, oh, you know, the greatest. So she was very impressed. So he sits down and he says, you know, Mr. Jones, we have lots of white lawyers who help us in the movie, but what we need a young Negro.

546
01:56:42,000 --> 01:57:09,000
So I said, Dr. King, I hear you. I said, I told Judge remaining, I'd be willing to work on your case in any way, but I just can't go down. I just can't travel. And then I told him, why, you know, and he asked me some questions about myself and I told him, but I told you about how I was raised, my mother's death and so forth.

547
01:57:10,000 --> 01:57:26,000
I'm shortening it. And he leaves. Now my wife turns to me. And with an unexpected attack dog syndrome. And she says, what do you think you are doing?

548
01:57:26,000 --> 01:57:41,000
That's so important that you cannot help this man that came all this distance to ask for your assistance. I said, hold on. And that's not quite true. He had a speaking engagement. He did not come out to see me.

549
01:57:41,000 --> 01:57:59,000
And besides, because of the new world picture, you got a sand cart in the cooking drawer stealing us, not my problem. Well, that's sort of like center over the top. That's Friday night Saturday night. I got another call this time. The voice is sacramentally sweet.

550
01:57:59,000 --> 01:58:15,000
Mr. Jones, yes, my name is Dora McDonald. You know, Mr. Jones, Dr. King, and joined so much is visited with you and Mrs. Jones, but you know, Mr. Jones, he forgot to invite you to be his guest at a church tomorrow.

551
01:58:15,000 --> 01:58:29,000
He's involved with Hills. He's going to be the guest teacher. And he was so like you and Mrs. Jones to join him. So I told my wife what the message was, she says, well, you may not be going to Montgomery, but you're going to that church.

552
01:58:29,000 --> 01:58:40,000
She didn't want to go. So I go to the church. And I had never heard Dr. King speak before. Never heard him. I mean, they pay attention to him.

553
01:58:41,000 --> 01:59:01,000
I was one third from the front of the full pit. And he gets up. He says, ladies and gentlemen, brothers and sisters, the text of my sermon today, as a role and responsibility of the Negro professional in aiding our less fortunate brothers and sisters, struggling to beat him in the South. So I said, one smart dude.

554
01:59:01,000 --> 01:59:20,000
Then he begins to speak. And he begins to describe what he's doing much more in detail and texturing. I had never heard or seen him speak before.

555
01:59:20,000 --> 01:59:46,000
More accurately, I had never heard another human being walking on two legs on this earth speak that way before. It was mesmerizing. It was like, you know, you could hear a pin drop. And he was, you know, as he was so intense.

556
01:59:46,000 --> 01:59:59,000
And he was so serious. And then he pauses during the course of the sermon. And he says, for example, there's a young man sitting in his church today.

557
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:12,000
My friends in New York, who are lawyers for whom I have great respect. My friends in New York tell me that this young man's brain has been touched by Jesus.

558
02:00:14,000 --> 02:00:25,000
They tell me that when this young man, a lawyer does any legal research, he goes all the way back to the time of 1066.

559
02:00:25,000 --> 02:00:42,000
We have a conch ran the Magna Carta. And then my friends in New York for whom I have great respect. Tell me that when he writes down what he finds in the law library, the words are so compelling, they just Daniel H. Krenge De Iongh't want the page.

560
02:00:43,000 --> 02:00:59,000
So I'm thinking to myself, he's not looking at me and I can't even inconceivable he could be talking about me because I'm thinking to myself, I'm a little bit of an opportunist. I'm saying, you know, when this church is over, I want to find out who that man is.

